1
00:00:03,080 --> 00:00:03,960
[COIN CLINKS]

2
00:00:04,080 --> 00:00:06,440
[♪]

3
00:01:07,320 --> 00:01:09,880
[♪]

4
00:01:40,920 --> 00:01:42,080
Oof!

5
00:02:31,360 --> 00:02:33,160
Yes, this looks
the sort of thing.

6
00:02:33,280 --> 00:02:34,280
May I just try it?

7
00:02:34,400 --> 00:02:35,760
Certainly, madam.

8
00:02:35,880 --> 00:02:36,840
Ooh!

9
00:02:36,960 --> 00:02:38,720
Sorry, so sorry.

10
00:02:38,840 --> 00:02:40,720
Yes, that's fine.

11
00:02:40,840 --> 00:02:41,840
Is that on account, madam?

12
00:02:41,960 --> 00:02:43,320
WOMAN:
Yes.

13
00:02:46,880 --> 00:02:47,920
Hello?

14
00:02:48,040 --> 00:02:49,000
[RINGS]

15
00:02:49,120 --> 00:02:50,280
Hello?

16
00:02:50,960 --> 00:02:53,160
[SQUAWKS]

17
00:02:55,640 --> 00:02:57,760
[SQUAWKS]

18
00:02:59,440 --> 00:03:00,680
[SQUAWKS]

19
00:03:01,920 --> 00:03:02,960
Oh, I'm terribly sorry.

20
00:03:03,080 --> 00:03:04,560
I thought you were
someone else.

21
00:03:04,680 --> 00:03:06,000
Oh, I see, yes.

22
00:03:06,120 --> 00:03:08,600
I'm-- I'm sorry, sir,
can I help you?

23
00:03:08,720 --> 00:03:10,840
Uh, yes-- Yes, as a matter
of fact you can, actually.

24
00:03:10,960 --> 00:03:14,880
I-- I was interested
in the possibility of pur--

25
00:03:15,000 --> 00:03:17,520
Can I ask you
who you thought I was?
What?

26
00:03:17,640 --> 00:03:18,960
Who did you think I was,

27
00:03:19,080 --> 00:03:20,640
just then, when you thought
I was somebody?

28
00:03:20,760 --> 00:03:22,400
Oh, it's no one
you'd know, sir.

29
00:03:22,520 --> 00:03:23,960
Well, I might know them.

30
00:03:24,080 --> 00:03:26,080
Well, it's possible,
but I think it's unlikely.

31
00:03:26,200 --> 00:03:27,160
I know quite a lot--

32
00:03:27,280 --> 00:03:28,240
He's hardly likely to move

33
00:03:28,360 --> 00:03:29,320
in your circle, sir.

34
00:03:29,440 --> 00:03:30,840
Why, is he very rich?

35
00:03:30,960 --> 00:03:32,480
Oh, no, I didn't mean that,
sir.

36
00:03:32,600 --> 00:03:34,520
Is he a lord, or something?
Oh, no. Not at all.

37
00:03:34,640 --> 00:03:35,480
This is very easy to settle.

38
00:03:35,600 --> 00:03:37,200
What is his name?
What?

39
00:03:37,320 --> 00:03:38,280
What is his name?

40
00:03:38,400 --> 00:03:39,800
Well, um--

41
00:03:39,920 --> 00:03:41,560
Yes?

42
00:03:41,680 --> 00:03:42,640
Michael Ellis.

43
00:03:42,760 --> 00:03:44,160
Who?

44
00:03:44,280 --> 00:03:45,880
Michael Ellis.

45
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:47,200
I see.

46
00:03:48,280 --> 00:03:49,280
Do you know him, sir?

47
00:03:49,400 --> 00:03:51,920
Oh, Michael Ellis. Um...

48
00:03:52,040 --> 00:03:53,000
Michael Ellis--

49
00:03:53,120 --> 00:03:54,480
You don't.

50
00:03:54,600 --> 00:03:55,840
Well, I don't remember
the name.

51
00:03:55,960 --> 00:03:57,000
I think you would
remember him, sir.

52
00:03:57,120 --> 00:03:58,640
Why do you say that?

53
00:03:58,760 --> 00:04:01,840
Well, would you remember a man
6-foot, 9-inches high, 40-ish,

54
00:04:01,960 --> 00:04:03,800
and he's got a scar from
here to here,

55
00:04:03,920 --> 00:04:05,120
and absolutely no nose?

56
00:04:07,120 --> 00:04:09,520
Oh, I think I do remember
somebody like that.

57
00:04:09,640 --> 00:04:13,120
Well,
that's not Michael Ellis.

58
00:04:13,240 --> 00:04:15,720
He's a small man
about this high,
with a high-pitched voice.

59
00:04:15,840 --> 00:04:17,440
Right, I'm not gonna buy
an ant from you now.

60
00:04:17,560 --> 00:04:19,720
Oh, no. Please?
I know you've
not been trained.

61
00:04:19,840 --> 00:04:21,560
I demand another assistant.
Oh, no, come on.

62
00:04:21,680 --> 00:04:23,160
I want another assistant.

63
00:04:23,280 --> 00:04:25,680
All right. I'll get
another assistant.
Thank you.

64
00:04:25,800 --> 00:04:27,320
Hello, sir,
can I help you, sir?

65
00:04:27,440 --> 00:04:28,680
No, I want
a different assistant.

66
00:04:28,800 --> 00:04:30,840
I am, sir.
I'm Mr. Abanazar, sir.

67
00:04:30,960 --> 00:04:32,080
Don't be silly.

68
00:04:32,200 --> 00:04:33,760
Oh, no, please,
please let me help you.

69
00:04:33,880 --> 00:04:35,520
No, I want another assistant.
Come on.

70
00:04:35,640 --> 00:04:36,880
If you don't give me
another assist--

71
00:04:37,000 --> 00:04:38,280
No, no,
I'll be very good, sir.

72
00:04:38,400 --> 00:04:40,280
Good morning, sir.
How are you, sir?

73
00:04:40,400 --> 00:04:41,520
Bit parky outside, isn't it?

74
00:04:41,640 --> 00:04:43,160
Very nice suit
you've got there, sir.

75
00:04:43,280 --> 00:04:44,520
You had a close shave
this morning.

76
00:04:44,640 --> 00:04:45,920
Right, I'm going.
No, no, no, please!

77
00:04:46,040 --> 00:04:47,000
I'll get another assistant.

78
00:04:47,120 --> 00:04:48,280
All right.

79
00:04:53,000 --> 00:04:54,440
Whoooo!

80
00:04:54,560 --> 00:04:55,680
It's not him.

81
00:04:55,800 --> 00:04:57,040
Oh.
I don't want him.

82
00:04:57,160 --> 00:04:58,080
Oh, please,
give him a chance.

83
00:04:58,200 --> 00:04:59,640
No.

84
00:04:59,760 --> 00:05:01,360
Yes, sir. Can I be
of any assistance?

85
00:05:01,480 --> 00:05:02,640
Oh, come on, don't try that.

86
00:05:02,760 --> 00:05:03,840
I'm sorry, sir,
try what?

87
00:05:03,960 --> 00:05:04,920
You know what I mean.

88
00:05:05,040 --> 00:05:06,560
I'm afraid I don't, sir.

89
00:05:06,680 --> 00:05:08,840
You were down there with a
silly mask on, going "whooo!"

90
00:05:08,960 --> 00:05:10,240
I don't think I was, sir.

91
00:05:10,360 --> 00:05:11,800
All right, get the manager.

92
00:05:11,920 --> 00:05:13,320
There seems to be some sort
of a misunderstanding, sir.

93
00:05:13,440 --> 00:05:14,800
Manager!

94
00:05:14,920 --> 00:05:15,880
This is the manager, sir.

95
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:17,720
What?
Yes, I'm the manager.

96
00:05:17,840 --> 00:05:19,280
Manager.

97
00:05:19,400 --> 00:05:21,080
It's a smashing store.
Can't recommend it too highly.

98
00:05:21,200 --> 00:05:22,200
Well lit, rat-free.
It's a joy to manage.

99
00:05:22,320 --> 00:05:23,520
Manager.
Oh, yes.

100
00:05:23,640 --> 00:05:25,240
Freshest haddock in London,
second floor.

101
00:05:25,360 --> 00:05:27,360
Third floor, Ribena.
Ants here.
Manager!

102
00:05:27,480 --> 00:05:29,080
Television and flame throwers
over there,

103
00:05:29,200 --> 00:05:30,680
our dinner-wagon
exhibition--
Manager!

104
00:05:30,800 --> 00:05:32,120
Quick!

105
00:05:32,240 --> 00:05:33,840
Yes, sir?
Can I help you, sir?

106
00:05:33,960 --> 00:05:35,960
Yes, I want to complain about
the assistants on this counter.

107
00:05:36,080 --> 00:05:37,720
Oh, I'm sorry to hear that,
sir. Which ones?

108
00:05:37,840 --> 00:05:38,840
Well, they're hiding now.

109
00:05:38,960 --> 00:05:40,760
Sir?

110
00:05:40,880 --> 00:05:42,800
They're hiding, down there,
behind the counter.

111
00:05:42,920 --> 00:05:43,880
I see, sir.

112
00:05:44,000 --> 00:05:45,800
[CHUCKLES]

113
00:05:45,920 --> 00:05:47,640
Well, there's nobody
down here, sir.

114
00:05:47,760 --> 00:05:49,800
Well, they-- They must've
crawled through here,

115
00:05:49,920 --> 00:05:52,080
crawled along and made their
escape through soft toys.

116
00:05:52,200 --> 00:05:53,920
Yes, of course.

117
00:05:54,040 --> 00:05:56,240
They were wearing masks and
going "whoo!", making noises.

118
00:05:56,360 --> 00:05:58,280
And one of them pretended
to be the manager.
Sir?

119
00:05:58,400 --> 00:06:00,400
He went, "Oh, yes,
I'm the manager.

120
00:06:00,520 --> 00:06:01,640
Smashing store to manage,
this.

121
00:06:01,760 --> 00:06:03,240
Freshest haddock in London."

122
00:06:03,360 --> 00:06:04,480
I think I've got it, sir.
I think I've got it.

123
00:06:04,600 --> 00:06:06,280
It's rag week. Heh.

124
00:06:06,400 --> 00:06:07,600
Rag week?

125
00:06:07,720 --> 00:06:08,880
Yes, you know,
for charity, sir.

126
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:10,360
Oh, I see.

127
00:06:10,480 --> 00:06:12,080
Some local college
or university?

128
00:06:12,200 --> 00:06:13,480
No, no, it's the store's
rag week, sir.

129
00:06:13,600 --> 00:06:15,000
The store's rag week?

130
00:06:15,120 --> 00:06:16,680
Yes. The senior staff
don't join in much.

131
00:06:16,800 --> 00:06:18,600
It's for the trainees,
really.

132
00:06:18,720 --> 00:06:20,040
Not very good
for business, is it?

133
00:06:20,160 --> 00:06:21,360
Oh, it's for charity.

134
00:06:21,480 --> 00:06:23,200
People are awfully good
about it, you know.

135
00:06:23,320 --> 00:06:25,320
I see, yeah.

136
00:06:25,440 --> 00:06:27,880
Right, sir.
Well, I'll get you
a senior assistant.

137
00:06:28,000 --> 00:06:29,440
Ants, was it?
Yes, please, yes.

138
00:06:29,560 --> 00:06:31,640
Mr. Snetterton?

139
00:06:31,760 --> 00:06:33,280
Could you look after--?
I don't want him!

140
00:06:33,400 --> 00:06:34,400
Oh, please,
give me a chance.

141
00:06:34,520 --> 00:06:35,720
No!

142
00:06:35,840 --> 00:06:37,520
All right.
Mr. Hartford.

143
00:06:37,640 --> 00:06:39,200
Yes, good morning, sir.

144
00:06:39,320 --> 00:06:40,720
Can I help you?
Yes, please.

145
00:06:40,840 --> 00:06:42,840
I'm interested in buying
an ant.

146
00:06:42,960 --> 00:06:45,280
Ah, yes.
And, uh, what price were
you thinking of paying, sir?

147
00:06:45,400 --> 00:06:47,560
Oh, well, I hadn't actually
got as far as that.

148
00:06:47,680 --> 00:06:49,240
Well, sir, they start
about half a P,

149
00:06:49,360 --> 00:06:51,320
but they can go
as high as 3P,

150
00:06:51,440 --> 00:06:53,320
or even 3 and a half P
for a champion.

151
00:06:53,440 --> 00:06:55,240
Uh, inflation, I'm afraid.

152
00:06:55,360 --> 00:06:57,920
Well, I should think one about
1 and a half P, please.

153
00:06:58,040 --> 00:07:00,520
You'll get a serviceable
little animal for that, sir.

154
00:07:00,640 --> 00:07:04,240
Quite frankly, the half-P ones
are a bit on the mangy side.

155
00:07:04,360 --> 00:07:05,400
What, uh--?

156
00:07:05,520 --> 00:07:07,400
What length was sir
thinking of?

157
00:07:07,520 --> 00:07:09,560
Oh, uh...medium?

158
00:07:09,680 --> 00:07:12,000
Medium. Medium,
medium, medium, medium.

159
00:07:12,120 --> 00:07:13,120
Yes, here we are.

160
00:07:13,240 --> 00:07:15,640
[CLEARS THROAT]

161
00:07:15,760 --> 00:07:18,920
Now, um, that one there
is an Ayrshire.

162
00:07:19,040 --> 00:07:24,440
And that one there is a
King George bitch, I think.

163
00:07:24,560 --> 00:07:27,240
And that one killing the
little flitbat is an Afghan.

164
00:07:27,360 --> 00:07:29,040
That's a nice one.

165
00:07:29,160 --> 00:07:30,560
Oh, well, let's see how
you get on with him, eh?

166
00:07:33,040 --> 00:07:34,520
Ah, yes, he likes you.

167
00:07:34,640 --> 00:07:35,800
He's taken to you.

168
00:07:35,920 --> 00:07:36,840
What do you feed them on?

169
00:07:36,960 --> 00:07:37,920
Uh, blancmange.

170
00:07:38,040 --> 00:07:39,560
Blancmange?

171
00:07:39,680 --> 00:07:41,280
I'm sorry, I don't know
why I said that.

172
00:07:41,400 --> 00:07:42,520
No, you don't feed them
at all.

173
00:07:42,640 --> 00:07:44,440
Well, what do they live on?

174
00:07:44,560 --> 00:07:45,920
They don't. They die.

175
00:07:47,000 --> 00:07:48,320
They die?

176
00:07:48,440 --> 00:07:50,160
Of course they do,
if you don't feed them.

177
00:07:50,280 --> 00:07:51,840
I don't understand.

178
00:07:51,960 --> 00:07:53,560
Well, you let them die.
Then you buy another one.

179
00:07:53,680 --> 00:07:55,160
It's much cheaper
than feeding them.

180
00:07:55,280 --> 00:07:57,240
You have a constant variety
of little companions.

181
00:07:57,360 --> 00:07:59,440
I see.
That's the advantage
of owning an ant.

182
00:07:59,560 --> 00:08:00,800
Well, I'll take this one.
Oh, dear, I've dropped it.

183
00:08:00,920 --> 00:08:03,200
Never mind.
Here's another one.
Thank you.

184
00:08:03,320 --> 00:08:04,640
Is there anything else
I'll need?

185
00:08:04,760 --> 00:08:06,720
Yes, sir, you'll need
an ant house.

186
00:08:06,840 --> 00:08:09,600
This is the, uh,
model we recommend, sir.

187
00:08:12,600 --> 00:08:13,720
Won't it get out of there?

188
00:08:13,840 --> 00:08:15,400
Yes.

189
00:08:15,520 --> 00:08:16,800
Then what's the point
of having the cage?

190
00:08:20,200 --> 00:08:21,520
Well, none at all really.

191
00:08:21,640 --> 00:08:23,200
Then some little pieces
of cage furniture,

192
00:08:23,320 --> 00:08:24,680
which will keep him
entertained.

193
00:08:24,800 --> 00:08:25,760
There's an ant-wheel.

194
00:08:25,880 --> 00:08:29,520
And there's
a little ant-swing.

195
00:08:29,640 --> 00:08:32,040
Here, sir, here's
a very nice one here,
a little ladder.

196
00:08:32,160 --> 00:08:34,240
He can run up, ring the bell,
that's a trick
he can learn.

197
00:08:34,360 --> 00:08:35,600
Will he live long enough?

198
00:08:35,720 --> 00:08:37,400
Not really, no.
But it's best to have one.

199
00:08:37,520 --> 00:08:40,720
And, um, here's a two-way
radio he can play with.

200
00:08:40,840 --> 00:08:43,280
And then of course
you'll need, uh, the book.

201
00:08:43,400 --> 00:08:44,560
The book?

202
00:08:44,680 --> 00:08:48,000
Uh, yes, yes. The, uh--
The book on ants.

203
00:08:48,120 --> 00:08:49,760
I see.

204
00:08:49,880 --> 00:08:53,920
So, sir, that is,
if I may say so, 184 pounds,

205
00:08:54,040 --> 00:08:55,320
one and a half P, sir.

206
00:08:55,440 --> 00:08:57,200
Well, will you take a check?

207
00:08:57,320 --> 00:08:59,440
Yes, sir, if you don't mind
leaving a blood sample

208
00:08:59,560 --> 00:09:01,400
and a piece of skin

209
00:09:01,520 --> 00:09:03,240
off the back of the scalp
just here, sir.

210
00:09:03,360 --> 00:09:04,960
Sorry, it's just for
identification, you know?

211
00:09:05,080 --> 00:09:07,320
Can't be too careful.

212
00:09:07,440 --> 00:09:08,880
Oh, I think
I'll put it on account.

213
00:09:09,000 --> 00:09:10,480
I should, sir.
Much less painful.

214
00:09:10,600 --> 00:09:12,160
Uh, there we are.

215
00:09:12,280 --> 00:09:14,240
Anyway, sir, you know what
they say about an ant.

216
00:09:14,360 --> 00:09:15,760
A friend for life, eh?

217
00:09:15,880 --> 00:09:17,040
Well, a friend
for its life anyway.

218
00:09:17,160 --> 00:09:18,560
Now, then, uh--

219
00:09:18,680 --> 00:09:21,960
Ah. Here we are.
His name's Marcus.

220
00:09:22,640 --> 00:09:24,400
Right.

221
00:09:24,520 --> 00:09:26,760
If the little chap should go
to an early grave, sir,

222
00:09:26,880 --> 00:09:28,400
give us a ring and we'll stick
a few in an envelope,

223
00:09:28,520 --> 00:09:29,560
all right?

224
00:09:29,680 --> 00:09:30,920
Thanks very much, indeed.

225
00:09:31,040 --> 00:09:32,200
Not at all.
Thank you, Mr. Ellis.

226
00:09:32,320 --> 00:09:33,880
Shhh!
What did you say?

227
00:09:34,000 --> 00:09:35,680
I said, thank you, Mr. Ellis.
It's not him.

228
00:09:35,800 --> 00:09:37,120
Why did you say I was
Mr. Ellis?

229
00:09:37,240 --> 00:09:38,160
Who?

230
00:09:38,280 --> 00:09:39,960
No, no,
he didn't say that.

231
00:09:40,080 --> 00:09:41,520
Yes, I heard him say,
"Thank you, Mr. Ellis."

232
00:09:41,640 --> 00:09:43,600
No, no, he said,
"I'm jealous."

233
00:09:43,720 --> 00:09:44,840
What?

234
00:09:44,960 --> 00:09:46,040
"I'm jealous of your ant."

235
00:09:46,160 --> 00:09:47,280
Goodbye. Goodbye.

236
00:09:47,400 --> 00:09:48,840
CLERK 2:
Bye-bye. Bye.

237
00:09:48,960 --> 00:09:50,920
I don't care
who Michael Ellis is.

238
00:09:52,520 --> 00:09:56,560
[MAN SPEAKING IN GERMAN]

239
00:09:56,680 --> 00:09:58,560
Excuse me, I was in the
ant counter a minute ago--

240
00:09:58,680 --> 00:10:00,920
[SPEAKING IN GERMAN]

241
00:10:05,200 --> 00:10:07,280
[SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

242
00:10:13,080 --> 00:10:15,200
[BELL DINGING]

243
00:10:24,520 --> 00:10:26,080
MAN [OVER PA]:
<i>Will Mr. Michael Ellis please</i>

244
00:10:26,200 --> 00:10:28,920
<i>go straight</i>
<i>to the manager's office.</i>

245
00:10:29,040 --> 00:10:30,600
<i>I'll repeat that.</i>

246
00:10:30,720 --> 00:10:33,080
<i>Will Mr. Nigel Mellish please</i>

247
00:10:33,200 --> 00:10:35,800
<i>go straight</i>
<i>to the manager's office.</i>

248
00:10:40,920 --> 00:10:42,720
What you got now?

249
00:10:42,840 --> 00:10:44,080
I bought an ant, Mother.

250
00:10:44,200 --> 00:10:45,560
Oh, devil.

251
00:10:45,680 --> 00:10:47,080
What do you want one
of them for?

252
00:10:47,200 --> 00:10:48,400
I'm not gonna
clean it out.

253
00:10:48,520 --> 00:10:49,640
You said you'd clean
the tiger out,

254
00:10:49,760 --> 00:10:51,360
but do you?

255
00:10:51,480 --> 00:10:53,320
No, I suppose you've
lost interest in it now.

256
00:10:53,440 --> 00:10:56,680
