We are here today on a
matter of national import.

504
00:22:29,040 --> 00:22:33,280
My late husband and we
are increasingly disturbed

505
00:22:33,400 --> 00:22:35,640
by recent developments
in literary style

506
00:22:35,760 --> 00:22:39,120
that have taken place here
in Germany-- England.

507
00:22:39,240 --> 00:22:40,360
There seems to be an

508
00:22:40,480 --> 00:22:42,080
increasing tendency
for the ant--

509
00:22:42,200 --> 00:22:43,440
Uh, the ant--

510
00:22:43,560 --> 00:22:45,800
The-- The ant to become
the dominant--

511
00:22:45,920 --> 00:22:46,880
[SPEAKS IN GERMAN]

512
00:22:47,000 --> 00:22:48,080
Theme.

513
00:22:48,200 --> 00:22:51,400
Theme among poetry
here in Germany.

514
00:22:51,520 --> 00:22:54,280
We are not, uh--

515
00:22:54,400 --> 00:22:56,600
Entertained.
Entertained.

516
00:22:56,720 --> 00:22:59,000
From now on,
ants is<i> verboten.</i>

517
00:22:59,120 --> 00:23:01,400
Instead it's skylarks,
daffodils,

518
00:23:01,520 --> 00:23:03,480
nightingales,
light brigades and--

519
00:23:03,600 --> 00:23:06,920
[SPEAKS IN GERMAN]

520
00:23:13,560 --> 00:23:14,800
Well, we must away now,

521
00:23:14,920 --> 00:23:16,880
or we shall be late
for the races.

522
00:23:17,000 --> 00:23:18,480
God bless you<i> alles.</i>

523
00:23:18,600 --> 00:23:21,080
[FANFARE PLAYING]

524
00:23:27,200 --> 00:23:29,240
MAN:
Psst!

525
00:23:29,360 --> 00:23:33,200
Electric kettles
over here, sir.

526
00:23:35,320 --> 00:23:36,360
Don't worry, sir,

527
00:23:36,480 --> 00:23:38,200
you're amongst friends
now, sir.

528
00:23:38,320 --> 00:23:39,840
Mr. Bradford, Mr. Crawley.

529
00:23:39,960 --> 00:23:41,680
These are our fitters, sir.

530
00:23:41,800 --> 00:23:44,160
We've had a lot of experience
in this field,

531
00:23:44,280 --> 00:23:46,520
and we do pride ourselves.
We offer the best

532
00:23:46,640 --> 00:23:49,960
and most discreet service
available.

533
00:23:50,080 --> 00:23:52,080
I don't know whether
you'll believe this, sir,

534
00:23:52,200 --> 00:23:53,720
but one of us is actually

535
00:23:53,840 --> 00:23:55,960
wearing a toupee
at this moment.

536
00:23:57,760 --> 00:23:59,240
Well, you all are,
aren't you?

537
00:24:03,000 --> 00:24:03,960
Have you got one?

538
00:24:04,080 --> 00:24:05,560
Yeah, but I thought you--

539
00:24:05,680 --> 00:24:06,640
I didn't know you.
I thought it was me.

540
00:24:06,760 --> 00:24:08,040
I thought it was me!

541
00:24:08,160 --> 00:24:09,280
So did I.
That is good.

542
00:24:09,400 --> 00:24:10,480
Oh!

543
00:24:10,600 --> 00:24:12,600
It is, yeah.

544
00:24:12,720 --> 00:24:13,880
Actually, I only came in here

545
00:24:14,000 --> 00:24:15,880
to ask where the manager's
office was.

546
00:24:16,000 --> 00:24:17,960
Just a minute,
someone told you
we all had toupees?

547
00:24:18,080 --> 00:24:19,040
No.

548
00:24:19,160 --> 00:24:20,240
Oh, yeah.

549
00:24:20,360 --> 00:24:21,480
How did you know?

550
00:24:21,600 --> 00:24:23,240
Well, it's pretty obvious,
isn't it?

551
00:24:23,360 --> 00:24:25,120
What do you mean,
obvious?

552
00:24:25,240 --> 00:24:26,960
His is undetectable.

553
00:24:27,080 --> 00:24:29,680
Well, it's a different color,
for a start.

554
00:24:29,800 --> 00:24:30,760
Is it?

555
00:24:30,880 --> 00:24:32,160
Of course it isn't.

556
00:24:32,280 --> 00:24:33,520
It doesn't fit in
with the rest of his hair.

557
00:24:33,640 --> 00:24:34,600
It sticks up in the middle.

558
00:24:34,720 --> 00:24:35,680
Well, it's better than yours.

559
00:24:35,800 --> 00:24:36,760
Yes.

560
00:24:36,880 --> 00:24:37,840
I'm not wearing one.

561
00:24:37,960 --> 00:24:38,920
[ALL LAUGH]

562
00:24:39,040 --> 00:24:40,000
Not wearing one.

563
00:24:40,120 --> 00:24:41,760
Why'd you come here in, then?

564
00:24:41,880 --> 00:24:43,120
They told me to find
the manager's office here.

565
00:24:43,240 --> 00:24:45,400
Oh, no, not again.

566
00:24:45,520 --> 00:24:46,520
Bit lame, isn't it?

567
00:24:46,640 --> 00:24:47,600
It's the truth.

568
00:24:47,720 --> 00:24:48,680
Manager's office.

569
00:24:48,800 --> 00:24:49,960
I mean, look at it.

570
00:24:50,080 --> 00:24:52,120
Where did you get that, eh?
Mac Fisheries?

571
00:24:52,240 --> 00:24:53,200
Ha, ha, ha, ha.

572
00:24:53,320 --> 00:24:54,280
Dreadful, isn't it?

573
00:24:54,400 --> 00:24:55,400
Nylon?

574
00:24:55,520 --> 00:24:56,960
It's not, it's real, look.

575
00:24:57,080 --> 00:24:59,920
Oh, anyone can do that.

576
00:25:00,040 --> 00:25:01,400
Come on, get it off.

577
00:25:01,520 --> 00:25:02,560
Look, do you want
a proper one?

578
00:25:02,680 --> 00:25:03,600
No, I don't need one.

579
00:25:03,720 --> 00:25:05,520
There's no need
to be ashamed.

580
00:25:05,640 --> 00:25:06,960
We've all owned up.

581
00:25:07,080 --> 00:25:08,440
I'm not wearing one.

582
00:25:08,560 --> 00:25:10,240
Don't you see,
this is something

583
00:25:10,360 --> 00:25:12,520
you've got to come
to terms with.

584
00:25:12,640 --> 00:25:14,080
I am not wearing a toupee.

585
00:25:14,200 --> 00:25:15,560
They just told me
to come in here

586
00:25:15,680 --> 00:25:16,720
to find the manager's office,

587
00:25:16,840 --> 00:25:17,840
to complain about my ant.

588
00:25:17,960 --> 00:25:19,760
Complain about an ant?

589
00:25:19,880 --> 00:25:22,040
Look, this is
for your own good.

590
00:25:22,160 --> 00:25:23,400
Ow!

591
00:25:26,760 --> 00:25:29,000
MAN:
All right. Take a seat.

592
00:25:29,120 --> 00:25:31,880
You see, it ought to have
a safety catch.

593
00:25:32,000 --> 00:25:33,680
I mean-- Ooh!

594
00:25:33,800 --> 00:25:36,840
I mean, what if this fell
into the wrong hands?

595
00:25:36,960 --> 00:25:39,520
Yes, madam. I'll speak
to the makers personally.

596
00:25:39,640 --> 00:25:40,920
Oh, would you?

597
00:25:41,040 --> 00:25:43,960
It would put my mind
at ease.

598
00:25:44,080 --> 00:25:45,040
Thank you.

599
00:25:45,160 --> 00:25:46,440
[FLAMETHROWER FIRING]

600
00:25:46,560 --> 00:25:48,360
WOMAN:
Sorry, oh, sorry.

601
00:25:50,040 --> 00:25:51,080
Next?

602
00:25:51,200 --> 00:25:53,000
He's still molesting her.

603
00:25:53,120 --> 00:25:56,000
Yes, yes, I'll see you
in a moment, sir.

604
00:25:56,120 --> 00:25:57,560
I've got a complaint to make.

605
00:25:57,680 --> 00:26:00,120
Ah, take a seat.
I'm sorry it's on fire.

606
00:26:00,240 --> 00:26:02,720
Oh, not at all.
I got used to this out east.

607
00:26:02,840 --> 00:26:04,600
Oh, where were you out east?

608
00:26:04,720 --> 00:26:07,760
Oh, Norway, Sweden.
Places like that.

609
00:26:07,880 --> 00:26:09,000
Oh, I'm terribly sorry,

610
00:26:09,120 --> 00:26:10,920
my suit seems
to keep catching fire.

611
00:26:11,040 --> 00:26:12,000
Extinguisher?

612
00:26:12,120 --> 00:26:13,680
Oh, no, thank you.

613
00:26:13,800 --> 00:26:16,040
I think we'd better
let it run its course.

614
00:26:16,160 --> 00:26:17,480
I was just thinking, uh,

615
00:26:17,600 --> 00:26:19,760
Norway is not very east,
is it?

616
00:26:19,880 --> 00:26:21,880
No, I should have said,
"When I was out north."

617
00:26:22,000 --> 00:26:24,120
Yes, sir. Are there
many fires in Norway?

618
00:26:24,240 --> 00:26:25,240
Oh, good Lord, yes.

619
00:26:25,360 --> 00:26:27,360
The place is a constant blaze.

620
00:26:27,480 --> 00:26:28,840
Wooden buildings,
do you know.

621
00:26:28,960 --> 00:26:30,280
Yes.
Mmm.

622
00:26:30,400 --> 00:26:31,760
No, I lost my wife
in Norway.

623
00:26:31,880 --> 00:26:32,880
Oh, I am sorry to hear that.

624
00:26:33,000 --> 00:26:33,960
Why, did you know her?

625
00:26:34,080 --> 00:26:35,480
No. No, I don't.

626
00:26:35,600 --> 00:26:37,440
Oh, she wasn't
a favorite of mine.

627
00:26:37,560 --> 00:26:39,960
No, we were out strolling
across a fjord one day

628
00:26:40,080 --> 00:26:43,240
when one of the local matadors
came out of his tree house

629
00:26:43,360 --> 00:26:46,440
and flung a load of old
scimitars and guillotines out

630
00:26:46,560 --> 00:26:48,520
that he'd got cluttering up
his wine cellar.

631
00:26:48,640 --> 00:26:50,840
And apparently, a rather large
proportion of them

632
00:26:50,960 --> 00:26:52,680
landed on my wife,

633
00:26:52,800 --> 00:26:55,040
causing her to, uh, snuff it
without much more ado.

634
00:26:55,160 --> 00:26:56,120
Yes, yes, well, look.

635
00:26:56,240 --> 00:26:57,920
[PA CHIMES]

636
00:26:58,040 --> 00:26:59,800
WOMAN [ON PA]:
<i>Here is an important</i>
<i>announcement</i>

637
00:26:59,920 --> 00:27:01,480
<i>about Michael Ellis.</i>

638
00:27:01,600 --> 00:27:03,880
<i>It is now the end</i>
<i>of Michael Ellis week.</i>

639
00:27:04,000 --> 00:27:06,400
<i>From now on,</i>
<i>it is Chris Quinn week.</i>

640
00:27:06,520 --> 00:27:08,000
What a rotten ending.

641
00:27:08,120 --> 00:27:10,080
Well, it is one
of our cheapest, sir.

642
00:27:10,200 --> 00:27:11,760
Well, what else have you got?

643
00:27:11,880 --> 00:27:13,800
Well, there's the long,
slow pullout, sir.

644
00:27:13,920 --> 00:27:16,160
<i>You know, the camera tracks</i>
<i>back and back and you mix.</i>

645
00:27:16,280 --> 00:27:18,280
[CHIMES RINGING]

646
00:27:18,400 --> 00:27:20,560
No, no, no. Have you got
anything more exciting?

647
00:27:20,680 --> 00:27:22,000
Well, how about a chase?

648
00:27:22,120 --> 00:27:23,360
There he is!

649
00:27:25,080 --> 00:27:28,360
[♪]

650
00:27:28,480 --> 00:27:30,240
Oh, no, no, no.

651
00:27:30,360 --> 00:27:31,720
Walking into the sunset?

652
00:27:31,840 --> 00:27:33,480
What's that one?

653
00:27:33,600 --> 00:27:36,400
You know, two lone figures
silhouetted against

654
00:27:36,520 --> 00:27:37,480
the dying rays
of the setting sun.

655
00:27:37,600 --> 00:27:39,360
[♪]

656
00:27:39,480 --> 00:27:41,120
The, uh-- The music swells,

657
00:27:41,240 --> 00:27:43,120
you've got a lump
in your throat

658
00:27:43,240 --> 00:27:44,960
and a tear in your eye.

659
00:27:45,080 --> 00:27:46,240
Oh, no.

660
00:27:46,360 --> 00:27:47,920
Pity, I rather like that one.

661
00:27:48,040 --> 00:27:49,440
They're all a bit
off the point, you see?

662
00:27:49,560 --> 00:27:50,800
Well,
there is one that ties up

663
00:27:50,920 --> 00:27:53,120
the whole Michael Ellis thing,
but, um...

664
00:27:53,240 --> 00:27:54,200
But what?

665
00:27:54,320 --> 00:27:55,280
Oh, no, nothing, nothing.

666
00:27:55,400 --> 00:27:56,480
Who is Michael Ellis?

667
00:27:56,600 --> 00:27:58,120
How about a happy ending, sir?

668
00:27:58,240 --> 00:27:59,840
Chris!
Thank God you're safe.

669
00:27:59,960 --> 00:28:01,800
No, you wouldn't want that,
would you?

670
00:28:01,920 --> 00:28:03,760
Why wouldn't I want that?

671
00:28:03,880 --> 00:28:06,640
Uh, what about summing up
from the panel? That's cheap.
What?

672
00:28:06,760 --> 00:28:09,080
You know,
the, uh, big match experts.

673
00:28:09,200 --> 00:28:11,360
I think that it was quite
a good show, isn't it?

674
00:28:11,480 --> 00:28:12,880
I think that the, uh--

675
00:28:13,000 --> 00:28:16,680
The Michael Ellis character
was a-- A little overdone.

676
00:28:16,800 --> 00:28:18,880
Well, I don't agree
with that, Malcolm.

677
00:28:19,000 --> 00:28:22,320
Uh, quite frankly,
the only bit I liked

678
00:28:22,440 --> 00:28:24,720
was this bit
with me in it, now.

679
00:28:24,840 --> 00:28:25,800
No?

680
00:28:25,920 --> 00:28:27,760
Slow fade?

681
00:28:27,880 --> 00:28:29,480
No.

682
00:28:29,600 --> 00:28:32,120
Well, uh, how about
a sudden ending?
